      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\docs\\standards\\coding-standards.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Coding Standards\n2: \n3: Non-negotiable rules for how I write code.\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## No PII in Repo\n8: \n9: **Never commit personal file paths, names, or identifiers.**\n10: \n11: `C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\...` is PII. It reveals a username, a directory structure, potentially a real name. Replace with `~/...` equivalents.\n12: \n13: **Rule:** Before any commit, grep for `C:\\Users\\` and replace with `~/`. Before any push, rewrite history if PII leaked.\n14: \n15: **Why:** A public repo with PII is a security risk and a privacy violation. Even if the data seems harmless, it builds a profile.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ## No Telemetry\n20: \n21: **No phone-home, no analytics, no tracking.**\n22: \n23: Not even \"anonymous usage statistics.\" Not even \"error reporting.\" If the user didn't explicitly opt in, don't send data anywhere.\n24: \n25: **Rule:** No `requests.post`, no `fetch()` to external URLs, no beacon scripts, no tracking pixels.\n26: \n27: **Why:** The user owns their data. That includes metadata about how they use the tool.\n28: \n29: ---\n30: \n31: ## Vendor Neutral\n32: \n33: **Never depend on one company's API or format.**\n34: \n35: If OpenAI shuts down tomorrow, AgentSON still works. If GitHub goes down, the CLI still works. If Supabase disappears, the local files still work.\n36: \n37: **Rule:** Every external service is optional. Every core feature works offline.\n38: \n39: **Why:** Vendor lock-in is the enemy of portability. The whole point of AgentSON is that it works everywhere.\n40: \n41: ---\n42: \n43: ## Single File Output\n44: \n45: **One .AgentSON file = one complete session.**\n46: \n47: No sidecar files, no database entries, no config dependencies. One file has everything: schema, entries, metadata, context.\n48: \n49: **Rule:** If you need a second file to understand the first file, the format is broken.\n50: \n51: **Why:** A single file can be emailed, shared, archived, version-controlled. Multiple files create sync problems.\n52: \n53: ---\n54: \n55: ## Minimal Dependencies\n56: \n57: **If you can do it in 20 lines, don't import a library.**\n58: \n59: Every dependency is a liability. It can be abandoned, hacked, or become incompatible. If the standard library does the job, use it.\n60: \n61: **Rule:** Check if `json`, `sqlite3`, `pathlib`, `hashlib`, `re`, `datetime` can solve the problem before reaching for `pip install`.\n62: \n63: **Why:** Dependencies are trust. Every `pip install` is trusting a stranger with your code.\n64: \n65: ---\n66: \n67: ## Test Against Real Data\n68: \n69: **Synthetic test data lies. Real data tells the truth.**\n70: \n71: Test fixtures should come from real sessions, not hand-crafted examples. Real data has edge cases, missing fields, weird encodings. Synthetic data is always clean.\n72: \n73: **Rule:** Every reader must have at least one test fixture from a real export.\n74: \n75: **Why:** If it works on clean data but breaks on real data, it doesn't work.\n76: \n77: ---\n78: \n79: ## Honest Labels\n80: \n\n(Showing lines 1-80 of 122. Use offset=81 to continue.)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1783287946736
